<p>
  Please log in with your <a href="https://www.qrz.com/">QRZ.com</a> username and password.
  <em class="highlight">It's free.</em>
</p>

<% if @error %>
  <p class="error"><%== @error %></p>
<% end %>

<form action="/login" method="post">
  <% if params[:net] %>
    <input type="hidden" name="net" value="<%== url_escape(params[:net]) %>"/>
  <% end %>
  <input name="call_sign" placeholder="call sign"/><br>
  <input type="password" name="password" placeholder="password"/><br/>
  <input type="submit" value="Log in"/>
</form>

<h2>A note about passwords.</h2>

<p>
  This server does <strong>not</strong> store your password. We only use it briefly
  to obtain a QRZ session identifier so this system knows who you are. (If you are
  interested, you can check out
  <a href="https://github.com/seven1m/ragchew.app/blob/master/lib/qrz.rb#L42">the open source code</a>
  where we send your credentials to QRZ and then discard them from memory.)
</p>

<p>
  But you don ºt have to trust us! There are many amateur radio software packages
  that want you to log in with QRZ, and you can protect your QRZ account by
  <a href="https://www.qrz.com/manager/two-factor">enabling Two Factor Authentication</a>.
  This prevents bad guys from messing with your account, even if they guess your password.
</p>

<p>
  As soon as QRZ.com implements industry-standard
  <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/OAuth">OAuth</a>, I will change RagChew.app
  to allow you to log in <strong>without</strong> typing your password here.
</p>

